recalls.Summary: Volkswagen Group of America, Inc. (Audi) is recalling certain 2015-2020 Audi S3 Sedan, A3 Sedan, 2016-2018 A3 Etron, 2017-2020 RS3 Sedan, and 2015-2019 A3 Cabriolet vehicles.  The passenger occupant detection system (PODS) may malfunction and switch off the passenger air bag even when the seat is occupied.
recalls.Consequence: A deactivated passenger air bag increases the risk of injury during a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Dealers will replace the PODS sensor mat and update the PODS control module, free of charge.  Owners letters were mailed December 23, 2021.  Owners may contact Audi customer service at 1-800-253-2834.  Audi's number for this recall is 69BY.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

issues.title: Carbon Build-up on Intake Valves
issues.description: Direct injection engines accumulate carbon deposits on intake valves, causing reduced performance, rough idle, and potential valve damage over time
issues.fix_description: Professional walnut blasting service to remove carbon deposits from intake valves
issues.prevention: Use high-quality fuel, perform regular Italian tune-ups, consider catch can installation

issues.title: Engine Mount Failure
issues.description: Engine mounts, particularly the upper engine mount, fail prematurely causing excessive vibration and noise
issues.fix_description: Replace failed engine mounts with OEM or upgraded aftermarket units
issues.prevention: Avoid aggressive driving when engine is cold, regular inspection of mounts

issues.title: Turbocharger Wastegate Rattle
issues.description: Internal wastegate actuator develops play causing rattling noise, particularly noticeable at idle or low RPM
issues.fix_description: Replace turbocharger assembly or rebuild with updated wastegate components
issues.prevention: Use high-quality oil, maintain proper service intervals, avoid excessive idling

issues.title: Transmission Fluid Leak
issues.description: S-tronic dual clutch transmission develops leaks from various seals and gaskets, particularly around the transmission pan
issues.fix_description: Replace leaking seals, gaskets, or transmission pan as needed
issues.prevention: Regular transmission service, avoid aggressive driving habits

issues.title: Brake Pad Premature Wear
issues.description: Front brake pads wear faster than expected, particularly on vehicles with aggressive driving or track use
issues.fix_description: Replace brake pads with OEM or performance aftermarket pads
issues.prevention: Avoid aggressive braking, regular brake inspection, proper bedding procedure

issues.title: High Pressure Fuel Pump Failure
issues.description: High pressure fuel pump can fail causing fuel starvation, poor performance, and potential engine damage
issues.fix_description: Replace high pressure fuel pump and associated components
issues.prevention: Use high-quality fuel, maintain fuel system cleanliness, regular maintenance

issues.title: Water Pump Failure
issues.description: Electric water pump fails leading to overheating and potential engine damage if not addressed promptly
issues.fix_description: Replace electric water pump and flush cooling system
issues.prevention: Regular coolant changes, monitor coolant levels, address leaks promptly

issues.title: Door Handle Mechanism Failure
issues.description: Electronic door handle mechanism fails, preventing door from opening from outside or inside
issues.fix_description: Replace door handle mechanism and associated components
issues.prevention: Gentle operation of handles, protect from excessive moisture

issues.title: Clutch Pack Wear in S-Tronic
issues.description: Dual clutch transmission clutch packs wear prematurely, especially with aggressive driving or frequent launch control use
issues.fix_description: Replace clutch packs in dual clutch transmission
issues.prevention: Avoid excessive launch control use, proper warm-up procedures, regular service

issues.title: Ignition Coil Failure
issues.description: Ignition coils fail causing misfires and reduced performance, particularly common on higher mileage vehicles
issues.fix_description: Replace failed ignition coils and spark plugs as needed
issues.prevention: Use quality fuel, replace spark plugs at recommended intervals

editorial.tagline: Five cylinders of fury in wolf's clothing
editorial.hero_blurb: The RS3 8V transforms Audi's compact sedan into a 400-horsepower missile with an unforgettable soundtrack. This is the five-cylinder symphony that makes supercars nervous at traffic lights.
editorial.essence: The RS3 8V houses one of the automotive world's most characterful engines - a 2.5-liter turbocharged inline-five that produces an intoxicating blend of power and sound. It's the thinking enthusiast's muscle car, wrapped in understated Germanic sophistication.
editorial.heritage: Born from Audi's Quattro rally DNA and TTRS lineage, the RS3 represents the culmination of decades perfecting the turbocharged five-cylinder formula. It carries forward the torch from legendary Quattro racers while adding modern refinement.
editorial.design_philosophy: Subtle aggression defines the RS3's aesthetic - wider haunches, aggressive front splitter, and RS-specific details that whisper performance rather than shout it. The designers wanted a sleeper that could surprise while maintaining daily usability.
editorial.motorsport_history: While the RS3 itself hasn't dominated racetracks, its 2.5T engine architecture proved itself in TTRS Cup racing and various touring car championships, validating its competition-ready credentials.
editorial.engine_character: The turbocharged five-cylinder is pure theater - building boost with urgency while delivering a distinctive off-beat rhythm that's immediately recognizable. Power delivery is linear yet explosive, with minimal lag and maximum drama.
editorial.transmission_feel: The seven-speed S tronic dual-clutch fires off shifts with surgical precision, delivering lightning-quick upshifts under full acceleration while offering smooth operation in comfort mode for daily driving.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: Quattro all-wheel drive provides unshakeable traction, allowing the RS3 to deploy its power with confidence in any conditions. The chassis feels taut and responsive, with minimal body roll and excellent balance.
editorial.steering_feel: Direct and well-weighted, the steering provides good feedback without being overly heavy. It's precise enough for aggressive driving while remaining comfortable for long journeys.
editorial.brake_confidence: Massive Brembo brakes provide fade-resistant stopping power with excellent pedal feel. The brakes inspire complete confidence even during repeated hard stops from triple-digit speeds.
editorial.sound_signature: The five-cylinder's distinctive warble evolves into a full-throated roar under acceleration, with pops and crackles on overrun. It's one of the most distinctive and addictive sounds in modern performance cars.
editorial.ideal_owner: Perfect for the enthusiast who wants supercar-level performance with practical daily usability, values understated style over flashy looks, and appreciates mechanical character over clinical perfection.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Those seeking pure track focus, buyers wanting maximum interior space, or anyone who prefers smooth, refined powertrains over characterful engines.
editorial.buyers_summary: Look for well-maintained examples with service history, as the high-strung engine demands proper care. The 2019-2020 models received minor updates but all years are solid choices for the discerning enthusiast.

expertReviews.title: Is the 8V RS3 Still WORTH IT in 2025? (POV Drive Review)
pros: Understated appearance blends with regular traffic
Incredible five-cylinder engine sound - unique in North America
Extremely fast in stock form with huge power potential
Practical daily driver with reliability
Staggered tire setup provides excellent grip
Complete package combining practicality with performance
cons: Very expensive - $46,000 for 7-year-old car with 84k km
Much higher maintenance costs than alternatives
Some turbo lag present
Less nimble feeling compared to S3
May feel too numb or not raw enough for some drivers
expertReviews.verdict: Owner is extremely satisfied with $46,000 purchase of 2018 RS3 with 84k km, calling it a dream car that exceeded expectations. Values the unique 5-cylinder Daza engine sound and complete package of performance, practicality, and reliability. However, acknowledges S3 offers similar experience for $20,000 less if you don't need the special engine character and uniqueness.

expertReviews.title: Which Audi RS3 is Better? 8V vs 8Y Real Differences and ...
pros: 8Y has more comfortable and supportive seats with better side bolsters
8Y suspension is more sophisticated with better tuning and stability
8Y interior is more refined with wireless charging and better space utilization
Both cars have excellent 5-cylinder sound and quick dual-clutch transmission
8Y has slightly more power (401hp vs 394hp) and quicker 0-60 times
cons: 8V has better steering ratio that feels more direct and responsive
8Y steering wheel lacks flat bottom design and requires more input
8Y costs significantly more on used market (at least $55k)
8V has cleaner, more traditional Audi design that ages well
Both cars have limited rear headroom for taller passengers
expertReviews.verdict: The 8Y RS3 offers meaningful improvements in comfort, interior refinement, and suspension tuning, making it feel more race-ready and confident. However, the 8V maintains superior steering feel and directness. While the 8Y is the better overall car with notable upgrades, the improvements aren't drastic enough to justify the significant price premium on the used market.

expertReviews.title: BETTER Than a 2025? Audi RS3 8V Interior Review
pros: Perfect steering wheel with Alcantara finish
Premium diamond stitch seats with red accented stitching
High quality materials and build throughout
Digital dash that doesn't look dated after 7 years
Carbon fiber accents add special feel
2018 model allows infotainment screen to be closed while driving
cons: Infotainment system starting to feel dated
Seats not the most comfortable for daily driving
2019+ models can't close infotainment screen while driving
expertReviews.verdict: The 2018 Audi RS3 interior remains exceptional after 7 years, with the reviewer calling it understated perfection. The diamond stitch seats are described as potentially the nicest in any modern car, while the Alcantara steering wheel and accents create a special driving experience. Despite some aging infotainment technology, the overall interior quality and design hold up remarkably well.

expertReviews.title: 2019 Audi RS3 Review - The BEST Sport Compact Ever??
pros: 2.5L turbo 5-cylinder engine with 395hp
Nearly 4-second 0-60 times
Dual-clutch 7-speed transmission
All-wheel drive Quattro system
Nimble and compact for city parking
Excellent engine sound
Good reliability
Understated styling
cons: Suspension stiffer than segment competitors
Poor rear seat space and comfort
Limited trunk space
Backup camera quality disappointing for price point
Cup holders fail for large bottles
Understated looks may be too subtle for some
expertReviews.verdict: The reviewer declares this the best compact sedan he's ever driven, praising it as a 'pocket rocket' that punches above its weight class. The 5-cylinder engine is the standout feature, providing nearly supercar-level performance in a practical compact package. While expensive, it's considered good value for the performance delivered. The car excels as a two-faced vehicle - comfortable for daily driving but transforms into a performance machine when needed.

expertReviews.title: Is The Audi RS3 Only Good Because Of Its Engine? | Driven+
pros: Glorious 5-cylinder engine sound
Exceptional acceleration (3.28-3.31 seconds 0-60)
Quattro all-wheel drive system
Daily usable and practical
High build quality
Good value at Â£30,000 used
Capable on track and country roads
cons: Understeer tendency on track
Can look like a regular A3 from certain angles
Less striking design compared to M cars
Screen not touchscreen
Soft limiter in comfort mode
expertReviews.verdict: The RS3 is not just good because of its engine - it's a brilliant all-rounder. While the 5-cylinder engine is the main attraction with its incredible sound and performance, the car excels as a daily driver with sharp suspension, capable Quattro system, and excellent build quality. At Â£30,000 used, it's a great buy that delivers smiles whether commuting or on track.

expertReviews.title: The HONEST Truth About Living with an Audi RS3 for 2 Years
pros: Holds value well - worth what they paid after 2 years
Very comfortable daily driver with great seats
Extremely fast and precise handling
Five-cylinder engine sounds amazing
Easy maintenance - oil changes only cost $70
Good dual-clutch transmission character
Works as family car with slim car seat
cons: Very cramped interior space for tall passengers
Limited rear seat headroom
Not practical for regular family use with baby
Dual-clutch transmission rough at low speeds
Standard car seats too big for the car
Battery issues if left sitting too long
expertReviews.verdict: After 2 years and 5,000 miles, the RS3 serves well as a backup family car but sits unused most of the time due to cramped interior and availability of press cars. Despite space limitations, it's an excellent asset that holds value, requires minimal maintenance, and delivers thrilling performance when driven. Perfect for those who can sacrifice space for excitement, but not ideal as a primary family vehicle.
